# Architecture

Follow **Hexagonal Architecture** (Ports & Adapters) with domain logic at the centre and infrastructure at the edges.

## Principles

- **Domain at the centre**: Business logic lives in the domain layer and has no dependencies on frameworks or infrastructure.
- **Ports define interfaces**: Inbound ports (use case interfaces) and outbound ports (repository, external service interfaces) are defined by the domain.
- **Adapters implement ports**: REST controllers, GraphQL resolvers, database implementations, and external API clients are adapters that implement ports.
- **Use cases**: See the use-cases rule for use case structure, orchestration, and handler wiring.

## API Strategy

| Context | API Style | Rationale |
|---------|-----------|-----------|
| General backend services | REST | Resource-oriented, standard HTTP semantics |
| Backend-for-Frontend (BFF) | GraphQL | Query-driven, flexible data shaping for UI needs |

Use REST for public or service-to-service APIs. Use GraphQL when building BFF layers that aggregate and shape data for specific frontends. See api-design rule for pagination, versioning, and idempotency standards.

## Monorepo Layout

```
<project-root>/
├── apps/           # Deployable applications
│   ├── web/        # Frontend app(s)
│   ├── api/        # REST API service(s) — owns its CDK stack
│   └── bff/        # GraphQL BFF (if applicable) — owns its CDK stack
└── packages/       # Shared libraries
    ├── domain/     # Domain entities, ports
    ├── core/       # Use cases, application services
    └── shared/     # Utilities, types, config
```

Shared packages must not depend on apps. Apps may depend on packages. Each app owns its infrastructure.

**Monorepo tooling**: Use Turborepo, Nx, or similar for task orchestration, caching, and dependency-aware builds when the monorepo grows.

## Infrastructure Stack Layout

CDK stacks follow a **three-stack policy**: Auth, Stateful, and Stateless. Auth and Stateful stacks have no dependencies; Stateless depends on both. See the infra-stack-policy rule for the full standard.
